<subSubSection pageId="40" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="40.[685,1172,194,746]" pageId="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,807,433,454]" pageId="40">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hatch" authorityYear="1957" box="[823,1082,433,454]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Phlaeopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="loganensis">
<emphasis box="[823,1082,433,454]" italics="true" pageId="40">Phlaeopterus loganensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from all other 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Phlaeopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[986,1120,459,480]" italics="true" pageId="40">Phlaeopterus</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
by having the apices of the elytra triangular in both the male and the female (
<figureCitation box="[1063,1161,512,533]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="37.[731,762,1027,1046]" captionTargetBox="[710,1190,195,1011]" captionTargetId="figure-267@37.[709,1191,194,1012]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="Fig. 29. Phlaeopterus species. Right mandibles, ventral view, of A) P. obsoletus, B) P. bakerensis, C) P. elongatus. D) P. bakerensis, humeral angle of elytron, dorsal view. Apices of elytra of E) P. loganensis, F) P. hatchi, G) P. filicornis female." pageId="40">Fig. 29E</figureCitation>
). Although 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mullen and Campbell" authorityYear="2018" box="[788,911,539,560]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Phlaeopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elongatus">
<emphasis box="[788,911,539,560]" italics="true" pageId="40">P. elongatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Casey" authorityYear="1886" box="[962,1079,539,560]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Phlaeopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="filicornis">
<emphasis box="[962,1079,539,560]" italics="true" pageId="40">P. filicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have the elytral apices triangular in the female, no other species of the genus has the elytral apices triangular in both sexes. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hatch" authorityYear="1957" box="[921,1172,619,640]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Phlaeopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="loganensis">
<emphasis box="[921,1172,619,640]" italics="true" pageId="40">Phlaeopterus loganensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mullen and Campbell" authorityYear="2018" box="[880,1010,645,666]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Phlaeopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="olympicus">
<emphasis box="[880,1010,645,666]" italics="true" pageId="40">P. olympicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and these two species can be distinguished by characters discussed in the Remarks section of the latter species.
</paragraph>
